main event: On November 14, 1957, the 601st ACWRON in Rothwesten, Germany detected three high-speed radar blips of unknown origin.
interesting points: The first target was initially detected at 1101Z, the second at 1144Z, and the third at 1755Z, all at different locations.
There was an unusual amount of electronic interference during the second and third sightings, which the radar maintenance officer was able to explain except for the targets being reported.
The first target initially appeared as a single blip, but then split into two blips that continued on parallel courses.
The targets were estimated to be traveling at speeds between 2,000 to 5,500 nautical miles per minute, which was considered extremely high.
The observers, including a lieutenant and a master sergeant, could not determine the cause or nature of the high-speed targets.
